     <int-org-section id="IO-WFTU.0001" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Activities</heading>
          <p>
      In May 2022 WFTU’s 18th Congress issued the Rome Declaration, which stated that the COVID-19 pandemic had contributed to the timing and depth of (though had not caused
      
      ) an ongoing systemic crisis of capitalism, deemed by the Federation to be unresolvable by ongoing interventions involving expansionary fiscal policy. The Congress adopted a set of Priority Tasks that were focused on strengthening the organization’s unity and underlying principles, such as defending at all costs the right to strike. It approved several priority objectives, including: a standard 35-hour working week with no reduction in salary, to be followed eventually by a four-day 28-hour working week (again with no reduction in salary); universal public social security and pensions; combating high prices, unemployment and privatizations; defending the lives and rights of immigrants and refugees; eliminating child labour in practice (as well as in law); implementing legislation aimed at supporting pregnant women; addressing the ongoing environmental crisis; and ensuring the operation of health and safety committees in the workplace. An International Committee for Promotion and Protection of Trade Union Rights and Freedoms was to be established.
    </p>
          <p>WFTU observes International Workers Day (1 May) and International Action Day of Trade Unions for Peace (1 September, declared at the 18th Congress). The Federation organizes a militant International Action Day annually on 3 October.</p>
     </int-org-section>
